Definitely not an authentic experience, but certainly a good one. Coming from the West Coast, I've grown up eating relatively authentic Bahn Mi. While Nam Nam is not serving up authentic viet eats, it certainly draws inspiration from the island nation. Each sandwich was filled with pickled carrots, cilantro, mayo, and meats. However the baguette was smushed flat, and definitely comes with NY styling.  My only real grip is that the meat and condiments were piled a little haphazardly, with all my carrots in a pile to one side opposite the meat. Overall I'd certainly come again if the desire for Bahn Mi strikes again, but just don't expect anything TOO authentic.

Bro. BRO. My friend recommended this place to me and it did not disappoint.  So I've been craving a banh mi. It could lead to some bias in my rating, but c'mon I was dummy hungry.  So I go to this place and I get my pork banh mi, and since I love bubble tea I get a mango one with the bubbles. No big deal.  So then I eat my banh mi, and bro, I loved it. The bread was well toasted, the flavors done right, and the sriracha on point. Mango bubble tea was also a nice kicker to the end and I loved it.  So yeah I'm gonna give this place five stars. What are you gonna do about it? It's good.

All this having been said, the prices were not particularly cheap. One would think that costs would be down and that would be passed on - but not the case. Eh. This hole-in-the-wall Vietnamese food joint is by far the best Vietnamese food that I've had in Brooklyn. The shop itself has no outstanding aesthetic attributes except for a few newspapers and magazines. It seems like most customers either take their meals to go, get it delivered, or if you're like me, ravenously inhale your food without restriction.  The grilled pork banh mi is a MUST. For $5.50, you get a crispy baguette sandwich packed with juicy grilled pork, carrots, cilantro, and cucumbers. The proportion of meat to veggies is perfect. The bun pork vermicelli noodles are also an excellent choice. They are flavorful and filling, but light enough for a hot summer's day.  The bubble tea here is not bad, but a little on the sweet side. The bubbles could also be a little bit firmer.  You can make everything spicy or extra spicy here. And if extra spicy still isn't enough for you, help yourself to the many sriracha bottles lying around.

Nam Nam knows how to make a banh mi sandwich! I went with chicken, since I'm not a huge fan of pork banh mi sandwiches or pork in general. The chicken was perfectly cooked and juicy. The meat wasn't chewy at all, which has been a problem with some banh mi sandwiches I've had in my life. The vegetables were really crisp and fresh, adding a nice snap to the texture. I loved the bread, which tasted really fresh and had a great crusty kind of texture, which lets me know that they get their bread fresh to customers. This place is really casual so there was no waiter service, but the person working the cashier was really friendly and helpful as I thought through which item on the menu I wanted. He was the one who recommended the chicken banh mi!

Probably one of the more expensive banh mi's I've ever had. I partially blame this on Brooklyn being Brooklyn, but rarely paying more than $3.75 for a banh mi in the Buford Highway area of Atlanta my entire life, $6-7 for a banh mi feels a little steep.  In regards to the banh mi itself, I had a spicy pork and my overall review would be "it's pretty okay." Not the best I've had, but not bad. They're pretty heavy on the carrots and are pretty skimpy on the cilantro and cucumbers, with no peppers or pickled daikon to be seen at all.  Again, overall, it's a bit pricey for banh mi standards and while it's not a place that comes to mind when I think "excellent banh mis," at the end of the day, Nam Nam still makes a decent sandwich.
